# 1. Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

## 1.1 Formal Academic Definition

In the KTU 2024 Scheme syllabus for **Web Designing (OEITT833)**, **The Browser Object** refers to the hierarchical collection of JavaScript objects provided by the web browser runtime environment. These objects allow client-side scripts to interact with the browser window, the user's screen, the navigation history, the URL/location bar, and the loaded document.

The browser exposes a tree of host objects rooted at the global **`window`** object. Each child object represents a specific facet of the browser:

| Sub-Object | Responsibility |
|---|---|
| `window` | Top-level global object; represents the browser window/tab itself |
| `navigator` | Information about the browser application (user agent, platform, language) |
| `screen` | Information about the user's display hardware (resolution, color depth) |
| `location` | Information about the current URL and methods to manipulate it |
| `history` | Access to the browser's session navigation stack (back/forward) |
| `document` | The DOM tree representing the loaded HTML page |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU Syllabus Highlight:** In Module 3, "The Browser Object" is typically assessed as a **short-answer / 3-mark** topic focusing on the **hierarchy, properties, and basic usage** of these host objects. You are *not* expected to memorize every property ŌĆö focus on the **standard, KTU-listed** ones.

## 1.2 Conceptual Analogy / Intuition

Imagine the **browser as a hotel**:
- The **`window`** is the **hotel building itself** ŌĆö the container for everything.
- The **`navigator`** is the **reception desk** ŌĆö it holds information about the *guest's* (user's) ID, language, and software.
- The **`screen`** is the **room's view** ŌĆö it describes the physical size and resolution of the window the guest sees.
- The **`location`** is the **street address plaque** ŌĆö the current URL the hotel is mapped to, and you can change it.
- The **`history`** is the **guest's diary of places visited** ŌĆö you can flip back/forward through the pages already seen in this session.
- The **`document`** is the **content inside the room** ŌĆö the actual HTML, text, images, and forms the guest interacts with.

> [!NOTE]
> In JavaScript, even variables declared with `var` at the top level automatically become properties of `window`. This is why `window.alert("hi")` and `alert("hi")` behave identically.

## 1.3 The Global Nature of `window`

Because `window` is the global object, every global JavaScript variable, every built-in function (`alert`, `prompt`, `setTimeout`), and every other browser object is technically a property of `window`.

```javascript
// Both calls are identical
window.alert("Hello KTU");
alert("Hello KTU");

// Global variable becomes a window property
var university = "KTU Kerala";
console.log(window.university); // "KTU Kerala"
```

## 1.4 Standard Metrics & Properties (Bold for Quick Recall)

- **`window.innerWidth` / `window.innerHeight`** ŌĆö viewport dimensions in **CSS pixels**.
- **`window.outerWidth` / `window.outerHeight`** ŌĆö entire browser window dimensions.
- **`navigator.userAgent`** ŌĆö identifying string of the browser.
- **`navigator.platform`** ŌĆö operating system platform.
- **`screen.width` / `screen.height`** ŌĆö total display resolution in **physical pixels**.
- **`location.href`** ŌĆö full URL of the current page.
- **`history.length`** ŌĆö number of entries in the session history stack.

> [!NOTE]
> **KTU Note:** All properties below return values are of type **string** or **number** unless otherwise specified. No DOM traversal is required for this topic ŌĆö it is purely the *Browser Object Model (BOM)*, distinct from the Document Object Model (DOM).

---

<!-- SECTION_1_END -->

<!-- SECTION_2_START -->
# 2. Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Formula Sheet

## 2.1 The `window` Object ŌĆö Detailed Breakdown

The `window` object is both a **Global Object** and a representation of the browser tab. Its responsibilities are:

1. **Global scope holder** ŌĆö `var` declarations attach here.
2. **Dialog methods** ŌĆö `alert()`, `confirm()`, `prompt()`.
3. **Timing methods** ŌĆö `setTimeout()`, `setInterval()`, `clearTimeout()`, `clearInterval()`.
4. **Size/position properties** ŌĆö `innerWidth`, `innerHeight`, `outerWidth`, `outerHeight`, `screenX`, `screenY`.
5. **Container of child objects** ŌĆö `document`, `navigator`, `screen`, `location`, `history`, `console`, `localStorage`.

### 2.1.1 Dialog Methods ŌĆö Step-by-Step

**Step 1 ŌĆö `alert(message)`**
- Purpose: Display a modal message box with an OK button.
- Returns: `undefined`.
- Blocking: Script execution pauses until the user clicks OK.

**Step 2 ŌĆö `confirm(message)`**
- Purpose: Display a modal box with OK and Cancel buttons.
- Returns: `true` if OK is clicked, `false` if Cancel is clicked.
- Use case: Conditional branching based on user consent.

**Step 3 ŌĆö `prompt(message, default)`**
- Purpose: Display a modal box with a text input field.
- Returns: The string entered by the user, or `null` if Cancel is clicked.
- Parameters: `message` (label), `default` (initial value in the field).

## 2.2 The `navigator` Object ŌĆö Detailed Breakdown

The `navigator` object exposes information about the **browser application** and the **client device**.

| Property | Description | Return Type |
|---|---|---|
| `appName` | Browser name (e.g., `"Netscape"`) | string |
| `appVersion` | Browser version + OS info | string |
| `userAgent` | Full user-agent header string | string |
| `platform` | OS platform (e.g., `"Win32"`, `"Linux x86_64"`) | string |
| `language` | Browser's primary language (e.g., `"en-US"`) | string |
| `cookieEnabled` | Whether cookies are enabled | boolean |
| `onLine` | Whether the browser is connected to the internet | boolean |
| `geolocation` | API to access user's geographic location | object |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU High-Yield Property:** `navigator.userAgent` is the most frequently tested. Example: `"Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Win64; x64) AppleWebKit/537.36 ..."`.

## 2.3 The `screen` Object ŌĆö Detailed Breakdown

The `screen` object describes the **physical display**, not the browser window.

| Property | Description | Unit |
|---|---|---|
| `width` | Total screen width | pixels |
| `height` | Total screen height | pixels |
| `availWidth` | Screen width minus OS taskbar/dock | pixels |
| `availHeight` | Screen height minus OS taskbar/dock | pixels |
| `colorDepth` | Bits used to represent colors (e.g., 24, 32) | bits |
| `pixelDepth` | Same as `colorDepth` in modern browsers | bits |

## 2.4 The `location` Object ŌĆö Detailed Breakdown

The `location` object represents the **URL of the currently loaded document**. It is both readable and writable.

| Property / Method | Description |
|---|---|
| `href` | Full URL (e.g., `"https://ktu.edu.in/page?id=1"`) |
| `protocol` | Scheme (e.g., `"https:"`) |
| `host` | Hostname + port (e.g., `"ktu.edu.in:443"`) |
| `hostname` | Hostname only (e.g., `"ktu.edu.in"`) |
| `port` | Port number as a string (e.g., `"443"`) |
| `pathname` | Path portion (e.g., `"/page"`) |
| `search` | Query string including `?` (e.g., `"?id=1"`) |
| `hash` | Fragment including `#` (e.g., `"#section2"`) |
| `assign(url)` | Loads a new URL (creates a history entry) |
| `replace(url)` | Replaces current URL (no new history entry) |
| `reload()` | Reloads the current page |

> [!NOTE]
> **Engineering Utility:** `location.href = "newpage.html"` is the classic JavaScript redirect. It is the BOM equivalent of clicking a link.

## 2.5 The `history` Object ŌĆö Detailed Breakdown

The `history` object lets scripts manipulate the **browser's session navigation stack** without exposing the actual URLs (for privacy reasons).

| Property / Method | Description |
|---|---|
| `length` | Number of entries in the history stack |
| `back()` | Equivalent to the browser's Back button |
| `forward()` | Equivalent to the Forward button |
| `go(n)` | Move `n` steps through history (negative = back, positive = forward) |

```javascript
history.back();        // Go to previous page
history.go(-2);        // Go back 2 pages
history.forward();     // Go to next page
```

## 2.6 KTU Formula Sheet / Cheat Sheet (Markdown Table)

> [!IMPORTANT]
> The table below is your **last-minute revision gold mine** for KTU exams on this topic.

| Object | Key Property / Method | Return Type | Example Output |
