# 3. Step-by-Step Derivations & Analytical Matrix

## 3.1 Exhaustive Walkthrough: A Complete Browser Object Demonstration

Below is a fully annotated JavaScript program that exercises every Browser Object. **Each line is explained** so you can reproduce it in your KTU lab record.

```javascript
// ============================================================
// FILE: browser_object_demo.html
// PURPOSE: Demonstrate the Browser Object Model (BOM)
// ============================================================

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>KTU Browser Object Demo</title>
</head>
<body>
    <h1>Open the Console (F12) to see results</h1>
    <script>
        // --------------------------------------------------------
        // STEP 1: WINDOW OBJECT ŌĆö Dialog methods
        // --------------------------------------------------------
        // alert() pauses execution; confirm() returns boolean;
        // prompt() returns string or null.
        // We use a try-catch style flow without halting the page.
        // --------------------------------------------------------

        // STEP 1a: confirm() example
        if (confirm("Welcome to KTU Web Designing. Continue?")) {
            console.log("User clicked OK");
        } else {
            console.log("User clicked Cancel");
        }

        // STEP 1b: prompt() example
        let name = prompt("Enter your name:", "KTU Student");
        console.log("Name entered:", name);

        // --------------------------------------------------------
        // STEP 2: WINDOW DIMENSIONS
        // --------------------------------------------------------
        // innerWidth/Height refer to the VIEWPORT (visible area).
        // outerWidth/Height refer to the WHOLE browser window
        // including toolbars/scrollbars.
        // --------------------------------------------------------

        console.log("Viewport width  :", window.innerWidth);
        console.log("Viewport height :", window.innerHeight);
        console.log("Window width    :", window.outerWidth);
        console.log("Window height   :", window.outerHeight);

        // --------------------------------------------------------
        // STEP 3: NAVIGATOR OBJECT ŌĆö Browser & device info
        // --------------------------------------------------------
        // appName is deprecated; all major browsers return
        // "Netscape" for historical reasons.
        // --------------------------------------------------------

        console.log("Browser name    :", navigator.appName);
        console.log("Browser version :", navigator.appVersion);
        console.log("User Agent      :", navigator.userAgent);
        console.log("Platform        :", navigator.platform);
        console.log("Language        :", navigator.language);
        console.log("Cookies enabled :", navigator.cookieEnabled);
        console.log("Online?         :", navigator.onLine);

        // --------------------------------------------------------
        // STEP 4: SCREEN OBJECT ŌĆö Display hardware info
        // --------------------------------------------------------
        // width/height = total physical resolution.
        // availWidth/availHeight = minus OS chrome (taskbar).
        // --------------------------------------------------------

        console.log("Screen width    :", screen.width);
        console.log("Screen height   :", screen.height);
        console.log("Available width :", screen.availWidth);
        console.log("Available height:", screen.availHeight);
        console.log("Color depth     :", screen.colorDepth, "bits");

        // --------------------------------------------------------
        // STEP 5: LOCATION OBJECT ŌĆö Current URL
        // --------------------------------------------------------
        // Decompose the current URL into its parts.
        // --------------------------------------------------------

        console.log("Full URL        :", location.href);
        console.log("Protocol        :", location.protocol);
        console.log("Host            :", location.host);
        console.log("Hostname        :", location.hostname);
        console.log("Port            :", location.port);
        console.log("Pathname        :", location.pathname);
        console.log("Query string    :", location.search);
        console.log("Hash/Fragment   :", location.hash);

        // --------------------------------------------------------
        // STEP 6: HISTORY OBJECT ŌĆö Navigation
        // --------------------------------------------------------
        // length = how many pages in this tab's history.
        // We do NOT call back()/forward() here because doing so
        // would navigate AWAY from this demo page.
        // --------------------------------------------------------

        console.log("History length  :", history.length);

        // --------------------------------------------------------
        // STEP 7: TIMING METHOD ŌĆö setTimeout
        // --------------------------------------------------------
        // setTimeout(fn, ms) executes fn ONCE after ms milliseconds.
        // clearTimeout(id) cancels a pending timeout.
        // --------------------------------------------------------

        let timerId = setTimeout(function() {
            console.log("This message appears after 2 seconds");
        }, 2000);

        // To cancel, uncomment the next line:
        // clearTimeout(timerId);

        // --------------------------------------------------------
        // STEP 8: Practical Use Case ŌĆö Detect Mobile vs Desktop
        // --------------------------------------------------------
        if (screen.width < 768) {
            console.log("Device category : Mobile");
        } else if (screen.width < 1024) {
            console.log("Device category : Tablet");
        } else {
            console.log("Device category : Desktop");
        }
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

## 3.2 Analytical Matrix: Method-by-Method Decision Table

Use this matrix to choose the right Browser Object method in any KTU exam programming question.

| Goal | Object | Method/Property | Code Pattern |
|---|---|---|---|
| Show info to user | `window` | `alert()` | `alert("Saved!");` |
| Get yes/no from user | `window` | `confirm()` | `if (confirm("Delete?")) { ... }` |
| Get text from user | `window` | `prompt()` | `let x = prompt("Name:");` |
| Detect screen size | `screen` | `width` | `if (screen.width < 768) ...` |
| Detect browser | `navigator` | `userAgent` | `if (navigator.userAgent.includes("Chrome")) ...` |
| Detect platform | `navigator` | `platform` | `if (navigator.platform.startsWith("Win")) ...` |
| Check connectivity | `navigator` | `onLine` | `if (!navigator.onLine) alert("Offline!");` |
| Get current URL | `location` | `href` | `let url = location.href;` |
| Redirect (with history) | `location` | `assign()` | `location.assign("home.html");` |
| Redirect (no history) | `location` | `replace()` | `location.replace("login.html");` |
| Reload page | `location` | `reload()` | `location.reload();` |
| Go back one page | `history` | `back()` | `history.back();` |
| Go back two pages | `history` | `go(-2)` | `history.go(-2);` |
| Delay code execution | `window` | `setTimeout()` | `setTimeout(myFunc, 1000);` |
| Repeat code | `window` | `setInterval()` | `setInterval(clock, 1000);` |
| Detect viewport width | `window` | `innerWidth` | `if (window.innerWidth > 1200) ...` |

## 3.3 Mathematical / Logical Derivations

While the Browser Object is mostly declarative, three **KTU-style derivations** frequently appear.

### 3.3.1 Derivation: Total Available Pixels on Screen

The **total addressable display area** (excluding OS chrome) is:

$$
A_{\text{avail}} \;=\; \texttt{screen.availWidth} \;\times\; \texttt{screen.availHeight}
$$

**Example (in pixels):**
- `screen.availWidth = 1920`
- `screen.availHeight = 1040` (1080 minus a 40-px taskbar)

$$
A_{\text{avail}} = 1920 \times 1040 = 1{,}996{,}800 \;\text{pixels}
$$

> [!NOTE]
> **Engineering utility:** Web designers use this to detect whether the user has enough resolution for HD video, large dashboards, or full-screen modal dialogs.

### 3.3.2 Derivation: Color Palette Size

The number of distinct colors a screen can display is:

$$
C \;=\; 2^{\texttt{screen.colorDepth}}
$$

**Example:** if `screen.colorDepth = 24`:

$$
C = 2^{24} = 16{,}777{,}216 \;\text{colors (TrueColor)}
$$

For `colorDepth = 32` (with alpha):

$$
C = 2^{32} = 4{,}294{,}967{,}296 \;\text{colors}
$$

> [!IMPORTANT]
> This formula explains why a 24-bit color depth is also called **"TrueColor"** ŌĆö it matches the limit of human color perception (~16.7 million distinct hues).

### 3.3.3 Derivation: Device Category Classifier (KTU Viva Classic)

A common KTU viva question is: *"Classify the device based on screen width."* The standard decision boundary is:

$$
\text{Device} =
\begin{cases}
\text{Mobile}  & \text{if } \texttt{screen.width} < 768 \\[4pt]
\text{Tablet}  & \text{if } 768 \leq \texttt{screen.width} < 1024 \\[4pt]
\text{Desktop} & \text{if } \texttt{screen.width} \geq 1024
\end{cases}
$$

This matches the **Bootstrap 5** responsive breakpoints and is the de-facto industry standard.

