# 4. Structural Diagrams & Schematics

## 4.1 The Browser Object Hierarchy

The diagram below shows how every Browser Object relates to the `window` global. **Read from top to bottom** ŌĆö children hang below their parent.

```mermaid
graph TD
    win["WINDOW Object Global Scope"]
    nav["NAVIGATOR Object Browser Info"]
    scr["SCREEN Object Display Hardware"]
    loc["LOCATION Object Current URL"]
    his["HISTORY Object Navigation Stack"]
    doc["DOCUMENT Object DOM Tree"]
    dia["Dialog Methods alert confirm prompt"]
    tim["Timing Methods setTimeout setInterval"]
    dim["Dimensions innerWidth innerHeight outerWidth outerHeight"]

    win --> nav
    win --> scr
    win --> loc
    win --> his
    win --> doc
    win --> dia
    win --> tim
    win --> dim

    nav --> navP["Properties userAgent platform language onLine"]
    scr --> scrP["Properties width height availWidth colorDepth"]
    loc --> locP["Properties href protocol host pathname search hash"]
    his --> hisP["Methods back forward go n Properties length"]
    doc --> docP["Methods getElementById querySelector Properties title URL"]
```

> [!NOTE]
> The `document` object belongs to the **Document Object Model (DOM)**, not the Browser Object Model (BOM). KTU Module 3 covers both, but they are distinct APIs.

## 4.2 Block-Level Functional Architecture: Page-Load Navigation Flow

This diagram shows **how the Browser Object is used in a typical "Back to Home" button workflow** ŌĆö a common KTU practical question.

```mermaid
graph TD
    A["User clicks Back to Home button"] --> B["JS Event Listener fires"]
    B --> C["Call history.back function"]
    C --> D["Browser pops current page off session stack"]
    D --> E["Browser loads previous page in history"]
    E --> F["Previous page onload event fires"]
    F --> G["navigator object re-queried for new page context"]
    G --> H["screen dimensions recomputed for responsive layout"]
    H --> I["location object updates with new URL"]
    I --> J["document object exposes new page DOM"]
```

## 4.3 Block-Level Functional Architecture: Login Redirect Pattern

This is the **classic "auth-guard" pattern** frequently tested in KTU practicals.

```mermaid
graph TD
    A["User submits login form"] --> B["JS validates credentials"]
    B --> C{"Is user authenticated?"}
    C -- "Yes" --> D["Call location.replace dashboard html"]
    C -- "No" --> E["Call window.alert Invalid credentials"]
    D --> F["Browser loads dashboard URL"]
    F --> G["history stack does NOT include login page"]
    G --> H["User cannot click Back to revisit login"]
    E --> I["Script continues without navigation"]
```

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Why `location.replace` and not `location.assign`?** Because `replace()` overwrites the current entry in the history stack. The user cannot press the Back button to return to a page they should not see again (e.g., a post-logout screen). KTU questions on this distinction are **very common**.

## 4.4 Reference Table: The Five Browser Objects at a Glance

| Object | Read-Only? | Writable? | Primary Use | Example |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| `window` | Mostly read-only | Some props (e.g., `name`) | Dialogs, timing, viewport size | `window.alert("Hi")` |
| `navigator` | Yes | No | Detect browser/device | `navigator.userAgent` |
| `screen` | Yes | No | Detect display | `screen.width` |
| `location` | Yes | Yes (URL props) | Read/change URL | `location.href` |
| `history` | Yes (length) | No (URLs hidden) | Back/forward navigation | `history.back()` |

