# 5. KTU 2024 Scheme Examination Question Bank & Topic Recap

## 5.1 Part A ŌĆö Short Answer Questions (3 Marks Each)

> **[KTU University Exam ŌĆö Model Question 1]** [3 Marks]
> **Q:** List the major objects that come under the Browser Object Model (BOM) and state the purpose of each.

**Model Answer:**

The Browser Object Model (BOM) is a hierarchy of JavaScript objects provided by the browser. The major objects are:

1. **`window`** ŌĆö The top-level global object representing the browser window/tab. It hosts all other BOM objects and provides dialog methods (`alert`, `confirm`, `prompt`) and timing methods (`setTimeout`, `setInterval`).
2. **`navigator`** ŌĆö Provides information about the browser application and the client's environment, such as `userAgent`, `platform`, `language`, and `onLine` status.
3. **`screen`** ŌĆö Provides information about the user's physical display hardware, including `width`, `height`, `availWidth`, `availHeight`, and `colorDepth`.
4. **`location`** ŌĆö Represents the current URL of the loaded document. Allows reading URL parts (`href`, `protocol`, `pathname`) and navigation (`assign`, `replace`, `reload`).
5. **`history`** ŌĆö Provides access to the browser's session navigation stack through `back()`, `forward()`, `go(n)`, and the `length` property.

---

> **[KTU University Exam ŌĆö Model Question 2]** [3 Marks]
> **Q:** Write a JavaScript snippet to display the browser name, version, and screen resolution of the user's system.

**Model Answer:**

```javascript
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<body>
    <script>
        // Step 1: Read navigator properties
        var browserName    = navigator.appName;
        var browserVersion = navigator.appVersion;

        // Step 2: Read screen properties
        var screenWidth  = screen.width;
        var screenHeight = screen.height;

        // Step 3: Display in a single alert
        alert(
            "Browser : " + browserName + "\n" +
            "Version : " + browserVersion + "\n" +
            "Resolution : " + screenWidth + " x " + screenHeight
        );

        // Alternative: log to console
        console.log("Browser:", browserName);
        console.log("Version:", browserVersion);
        console.log("Resolution:", screenWidth, "x", screenHeight);
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

**Explanation of steps:**
- **Step 1** ŌĆö `navigator.appName` and `navigator.appVersion` are standard read-only properties exposed by the browser.
- **Step 2** ŌĆö `screen.width` and `screen.height` return the user's full display resolution in pixels.
- **Step 3** ŌĆö `alert()` displays the combined info in a modal dialog (alternatively, `document.write()` could be used to render it on the page).

---

## 5.2 Part B ŌĆö Long Answer Questions (14 Marks Each)

> **[KTU University Exam ŌĆö Model Question Paper Pattern]**
> KTU Part B questions offer an **internal choice**: the student answers **either** Question A **or** Question B. Each 14-mark question is split into two 7-mark sub-parts.

---

### **Question A (14 Marks)** ŌĆö Comprehensive BOM Coverage

> **Q (a)** [7 Marks] ŌĆö Explain the `window` object in JavaScript. List at least six of its important properties and methods with one-line descriptions.

> **Q (b)** [7 Marks] ŌĆö Write a complete HTML page that uses **all five** Browser Objects (`window`, `navigator`, `screen`, `location`, `history`) to display their key properties on the page using `document.write`.

---

#### **Solution to Q (a)**

The **`window` object** is the **top-level global object** in the browser's JavaScript runtime. It represents the browser window or tab currently displaying the page. Every global variable, every built-in function, and every other BOM object is a property of `window`.

**Key Properties:**

| Property | Description |
|---|---|
| `window.innerWidth` | Width of the viewport in CSS pixels |
| `window.innerHeight` | Height of the viewport in CSS pixels |
| `window.outerWidth` | Total width of the browser window including chrome |
| `window.outerHeight` | Total height of the browser window |
| `window.name` | A writable string used to name the window (persists across navigations in older browsers) |
| `window.length` | Number of `<iframe>` elements in the current window |
| `window.closed` | Boolean ŌĆö whether the window has been closed |
| `window.opener` | Reference to the window that opened this one (or `null`) |

**Key Methods:**

| Method | Description |
|---|---|
| `alert(message)` | Displays a modal message box with an OK button |
| `confirm(message)` | Displays a modal box; returns `true`/`false` based on user choice |
| `prompt(message, default)` | Displays a modal box with a text input; returns entered string or `null` |
| `setTimeout(fn, ms)` | Executes `fn` once after `ms` milliseconds; returns a timer ID |
| `setInterval(fn, ms)` | Executes `fn` repeatedly every `ms` milliseconds; returns a timer ID |
| `clearTimeout(id)` | Cancels a `setTimeout` callback |
| `clearInterval(id)` | Cancels a `setInterval` callback |
| `open(url, name, specs)` | Opens a new browser window/tab |
| `close()` | Closes the current window (only works on windows opened with `window.open`) |
| `focus()` / `blur()` | Sets/removes keyboard focus on the window |
| `scrollTo(x, y)` / `scrollBy(dx, dy)` | Programmatically scrolls the window |

**Why it matters:** The `window` object is the **root of all client-side JavaScript**. Understanding it is foundational to writing any interactive web page.

