#### **Solution to Q (b)**

**Comparison Table:**

| Feature | `location.assign(url)` | `location.replace(url)` | `location.reload()` |
|---|---|---|---|
| **Purpose** | Loads a new URL | Replaces the current URL | Reloads the current page |
| **History entry created?** | **Yes** ŌĆö a new entry is added | **No** ŌĆö current entry is overwritten | **No** ŌĆö the existing entry is refreshed |
| **Back button works?** | Yes ŌĆö user can return | No ŌĆö the original page is gone | No meaningful change |
| **Use case** | Normal navigation (e.g., clicking a link) | Post-logout redirects, auth-guard flows | Refreshing dynamic content |
| **Example** | `location.assign("home.html")` | `location.replace("login.html")` | `location.reload()` |

**Demonstration HTML Page:**

```javascript
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <title>KTU Location Methods Demo</title>
    <style>
        body { font-family: Arial, sans-serif; padding: 20px; }
        button { padding: 10px 20px; margin: 5px; cursor: pointer; }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <h1>Location &amp; History Methods Demo</h1>
    <p>Current URL: <strong id="url"></strong></p>
    <p>History length: <strong id="hlen"></strong></p>

    <hr>

    <h3>1. location.assign() ŌĆö Navigate (with history entry)</h3>
    <p>Loads a new page. Back button will return to this page.</p>
    <button onclick="location.assign('https://ktu.edu.in')">
        Go to KTU Website
    </button>

    <h3>2. location.replace() ŌĆö Navigate (no history entry)</h3>
    <p>Replaces this page. Back button will NOT return here.</p>
    <button onclick="location.replace('https://www.w3.org')">
        Replace with W3C Site
    </button>

    <h3>3. location.reload() ŌĆö Reload current page</h3>
    <p>Refreshes the current page from the server.</p>
    <button onclick="location.reload()">
        Reload This Page
    </button>

    <h3>4. history.back() ŌĆö Go to previous page</h3>
    <p>Equivalent to clicking the browser's Back button.</p>
    <button onclick="history.back()">
        Go Back
    </button>

    <h3>5. history.go(n) ŌĆö Jump n steps in history</h3>
    <p>Negative goes back, positive goes forward.</p>
    <button onclick="history.go(-2)">Go Back 2 Pages</button>
    <button onclick="history.go(1)">Go Forward 1 Page</button>

    <script>
        document.getElementById("url").textContent = location.href;
        document.getElementById("hlen").textContent = history.length;
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

**Step-by-step explanation of each method:**

1. **`location.assign(url)`** ŌĆö The browser navigates to `url` and pushes a new entry onto the history stack. Pressing Back returns the user to the previous page.
2. **`location.replace(url)`** ŌĆö The browser navigates to `url` and **overwrites** the current entry in the history stack. This is used when you do not want the user to navigate back (e.g., after a logout).
3. **`location.reload()`** ŌĆö The browser refetches and re-renders the current page. Useful for refreshing dynamic data without manually changing the URL.
4. **`history.back()`** ŌĆö Moves one step backward in the history stack, equivalent to clicking the browser's Back button.
5. **`history.go(n)`** ŌĆö Moves `n` steps. `history.go(-1)` is the same as `history.back()`; `history.go(1)` is the same as `history.forward()`.

> [!WARNING]
> **KTU Examiner's Valuation Warning / Common Pitfalls:**
> 1. **Confusing `assign` and `replace`** ŌĆö Many students write `location.replace` when they mean `location.assign` (or vice versa). The key distinction is the **history stack behavior**. Marks are awarded for explaining *why* one is preferred over the other in a given scenario.
> 2. **Forgetting parentheses on methods** ŌĆö Writing `location.reload` (without `()`) returns the **function object**, it does not call it. Always write `location.reload()`.
> 3. **Treating `navigator.appName` as truthful** ŌĆö Do not write code that branches on `navigator.appName == "Chrome"` for browser detection. It is unreliable. Use feature detection (`'geolocation' in navigator`) instead. KTU examiners often deduct marks for this.
> 4. **Mixing up `innerWidth` and `outerWidth`** ŌĆö `innerWidth` is the **viewport** (content area); `outerWidth` is the **entire window** including toolbars/scrollbars. A wrong answer loses up to 2 marks.
> 5. **Calling `history.back()` during an exam demo** ŌĆö This will navigate away from your demonstration page and the examiner may not see the rest of your code. Comment it out or wrap it in a confirm dialog before demonstrating live.

